node.text:
Seeing this nearly 90 year old footage in higher detail + color gives me a new appreciation for the Tasmanian tiger 🤩! This helps me really imagine what this animal looks & feels like. I can totally envision the hands-on element of what it might be like to work with this special predatory marsupial 🇦🇺 

Repost from @forrest.galante 
The 35mm negative of the last known Tasmanian tiger, named Benjamin, was scanned into 4K and colorized by experts in France.

They used rotoscoping as well as AI algorithms to make Benjamin true colors come to life. All in all the process took over 200 hours and in my option was worth every single second to give us a glimpse of this amazing creatures beauty.

node.text: I’ve been MIA after a 2+ week trip in South Africa working with @rhino911npo and had family in town for 2 weeks right after that but I can’t wait to share more about what I’ve been up to! node.text: This is the first part of an intimate discussion with long-distance swimmer Ben Lecomte, documentary filmmaker Jared McGilliard, and ocean advocate and @seeker host @danniwashington about "The Swim," an incredible documentary following Ben's attempt to swim across the Pacific Ocean to raise awareness for ocean health. The film, the full discussion, and lots of other great bonus content is now streaming on @discoveryplus . Subscribe now to start streaming: http://bit.ly/dplus-ig

node.text:
Episode 8: Octopuses 🐙 

If there's one species on this planet I question could be an alien life form I think it would be the octopus! Watch our finale episode of season 1 "Tusks To Tails" to see what I mean 😋

FYI Octopuses think, feel, and smell with their arms — so scientists are using them as inspiration for innovations in material science, medicine, and soft robotics. 
@seeker

node.text:
Seeing this nearly 90 year old footage in higher detail + color gives me a new appreciation for the Tasmanian tiger 🤩! This helps me really imagine what this animal looks & feels like. I can totally envision the hands-on element of what it might be like to work with this special predatory marsupial 🇦🇺 

Repost from @forrest.galante 
The 35mm negative of the last known Tasmanian tiger, named Benjamin, was scanned into 4K and colorized by experts in France.

They used rotoscoping as well as AI algorithms to make Benjamin true colors come to life. All in all the process took over 200 hours and in my option was worth every single second to give us a glimpse of this amazing creatures beauty.

node.text:
How did this happen❓
ANSWER: BELT SANDER
1️⃣ Snapping turtle 
2️⃣Belt sander
3️⃣Sting ray
4️⃣Electric wood planer
5️⃣North American beaver
6️⃣Samurai sword 

Patient was a 36 year old male intact H. sapien under the influence of enthusiasm & mild sleep deprivation. Lesion visually assessed, depth approached 0-2mm superficial to bone at distomedial aspect. Flushed copiously with dilute betadine in sterile saline then packed with OTC antibiotic ointment and bandaged closed. Daily bandage changes & assessments for secondary intention granulation tissue healing x 7 days. Patient complained about an “icky feeling” concerning his severed & jagged fingernail + exposed nail bed but lesion otherwise healed without complications and distal digit returned to full function. 
#dvmnotmd

node.text: He’s a good lil’ traveler 🐶

#question Baby Seal or Sea Lion❓
@marinemammalcare 
ANSWER: SEA LION 
This adorable pinniped orphan rescue was just beginning her rehabilitation process before being released back into the wild. Tube feeding is often a part of ensuring adequate nutrition. 
This is very important early on for juvenile animals and especially for seals & sea lions since their mothers provide some of the most nutrient dense milks of all mammals. 
@marinemammalcare is doing a terrific job at getting our marine mammals the care they need and back in the wild where they belong 🦭💙
#wildlife #conservation

node.text:
“Long” turtles 😂… #snakes ❗️
Going to the creek was my FAV thing to do as a kid. Looking for neato reptiles, amphibians & insects was on my daily to-do list in those days. 
Seeking wildlife with my lil buddy, Bear and experiencing it thru his eyes brings me back to that childhood passion I’ve always had and makes these wildlife adventures special in new ways 🐸💫
It seems you don’t have to go far to show children our fascinating natural world. For those animal-loving kiddos our own back yards or local parks can get them as stoked as anything 🤓. 
@tim_diggs

node.text:
Willdife medicine is no joke and the potential for harm is even greater with the world’s biggest terrestrial animal, even when they’re sedated. And the risk potential is very high for our wildlife too. The individual spontaneously performing the African elephant assisted no-hands somersault surely realizes things could’ve been worse for him. 
#wildlife #medicine 🌍
